# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: multivariate-statistics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In statistics, **correlation** is a type of statistical relationship between two random variables or bivariate data.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] It usually refers to the extent to which a pair of quantities are linearly related.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] More generally, an arbitrary relationship between variables is called an **association**, meaning the degree to which the variability in one can be accounted for by the other.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The presence of a correlation is not sufficient to infer the presence of a causal relationship, and this is often stated as "correlation does not imply causation".
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Furthermore, the concept of correlation is not the same as dependence: if two variables are independent, then they are uncorrelated, but the opposite is not necessarily true – even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might be dependent on each other.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Correlations are useful because they can indicate a predictive relationship that can be exploited in practice.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For example, an electrical utility may produce less power on a mild day based on the correlation between electricity demand and weather.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In this example, there is a causal relationship, because extreme weather causes people to use more electricity for heating or cooling.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] There are several correlation coefficients that may be used to measure correlation, often denoted $\rho$ or r .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The most common of these is the **Pearson correlation coefficient**, which is sensitive only to a linear relationship between two variables (which in turn may be present even when one variable is a nonlinear function of the other).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Other correlation coefficients, such as **Spearman's rank correlation coefficient**, have been developed to be more robust than Pearson's and to detect less structured relationships between variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The concept has been generalized to other forms of association between two variables, such as mutual information and distance covariance.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The most familiar measure of dependence between two quantities is the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient, most commonly called 'Pearson's correlation coefficient' or simply 'the correlation coefficient' (as it is the most common variant).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] It is obtained by taking the ratio of the covariance between two variables of a numerical dataset normalized to the square root of their variances.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Equivalently, Pearson's correlation coefficient can be calculated by dividing the covariance of the two variables by the product of their standard deviations.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Karl Pearson developed the coefficient from a similar idea by Francis Galton.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] A Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient attempts to establish a line of best fit through a dataset of two variables by essentially laying out the expected values and the resulting Pearson's correlation coefficient indicates how far away the actual dataset is from the expected values.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Depending on the sign of the Pearson's correlation coefficient, the result can be either a negative or positive correlation if there is any sort of relationship between the variables in the data set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator, $\operatorname {cov}$ means covariance, and $\operatorname {corr}$ is a widely used alternative notation for the correlation coefficient.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The Pearson correlation is defined only if both standard deviations are finite and positive.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] It is a corollary of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality that the absolute value of the Pearson correlation coefficient is not bigger than 1.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Therefore, the value of a correlation coefficient ranges between −1 and +1.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] As it approaches zero there is less of a relationship (closer to uncorrelated).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The closer the coefficient is to either −1 or 1, the stronger the correlation between the variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] If the variables are independent, Pearson's correlation coefficient is 0.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] However, because the correlation coefficient detects only linear dependencies between two variables, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] A correlation coefficient of 0 does not imply that the variables are independent.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For example, suppose the random variable X is symmetrically distributed about zero, and $Y=X^{2}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Then Y is completely determined by X , so that X and Y are perfectly dependent, but their correlation is zero; they are uncorrelated.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] However, in the special case when X and Y are jointly normal, uncorrelatedness is equivalent to independence.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Even though uncorrelated data does not necessarily imply independence, one can check if random variables are independent if their mutual information is 0.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Given a series of n measurements of the pair $(X_{i},Y_{i})$ indexed by $i=1,\ldots ,n$ , the *sample correlation coefficient* can be used to estimate the population Pearson correlation $\rho _{X,Y}$ between X and Y .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] where ${\overline {x}}$ and ${\overline {y}}$ are the sample means of X and Y , and $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the corrected sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] where $s'_{x}$ and $s'_{y}$ are the *uncorrected* sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] If x and y are results of measurements that contain measurement error, the realistic limits on the correlation coefficient are not −1 to +1 but a smaller range.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For the case of a linear model with a single independent variable, the coefficient of determination (R squared) is the square of $r_{xy}$ , Pearson's product-moment coefficient.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Consider the joint probability distribution of X and Y given in the table below.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Rank correlation coefficients, such as Spearman's rank correlation coefficient and Kendall's rank correlation coefficient (τ) measure the extent to which, as one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase, without requiring that increase to be represented by a linear relationship.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] If, as the one variable increases, the other *decreases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be negative.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] It is common to regard these rank correlation coefficients as alternatives to Pearson's coefficient, used either to reduce the amount of calculation or to make the coefficient less sensitive to non-normality in distributions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] As we go from each pair to the next pair, x increases, and so does y .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This relationship is perfect, in the sense that an increase in x is *always* accompanied by an increase in y .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This means that we have a perfect rank correlation, and both Spearman's and Kendall's correlation coefficients are 1, whereas in this example Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient is 0.7544, indicating that the points are far from lying on a straight line.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In the same way if y always *decreases* when x *increases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be −1, while the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient may or may not be close to −1, depending on how close the points are to a straight line.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Although in the extreme cases of perfect rank correlation the two coefficients are both equal (being both +1 or both −1), this is not generally the case, and so values of the two coefficients cannot meaningfully be compared.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For example, for the three pairs (1, 1) (2, 3) (3, 2) Spearman's coefficient is 1/2, while Kendall's coefficient is 1/3.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The conventional dictum that "correlation does not imply causation" means that correlation cannot be used by itself to infer a causal relationship between the variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This dictum should not be taken to mean that correlations cannot indicate the potential existence of causal relations.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] However, the causes underlying the correlation, if any, may be indirect and unknown, and high correlations also overlap with identity relations (tautologies), where no causal process exists (e.g., between two variables measuring the same construct).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Consequently, a correlation between two variables is not a sufficient condition to establish a causal relationship (in either direction).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] A correlation between age and height in children is fairly causally transparent, but a correlation between mood and health in people is less so.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Does improved mood lead to improved health, or does good health lead to good mood, or both?
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Or does some other factor underlie both?
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In other words, a correlation can be taken as evidence for a possible causal relationship, but cannot indicate what the causal relationship, if any, might be.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The Pearson correlation coefficient indicates the strength of a *linear* relationship between two variables, but its value generally does not completely characterize their relationship.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In particular, if the conditional mean of Y given X , denoted $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ , is not linear in X , the correlation coefficient will not fully determine the form of $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The adjacent image shows scatter plots of Anscombe's quartet, a set of four different pairs of variables created by Francis Anscombe.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The four y variables have the same mean (7.5), variance (4.12), correlation (0.816) and regression line ( ${\textstyle y=3+0.5x}$ ).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] However, as can be seen on the plots, the distribution of the variables is very different.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The first one (top left) seems to be distributed normally, and corresponds to what one would expect when considering two variables correlated and following the assumption of normality.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The second one (top right) is not distributed normally; while an obvious relationship between the two variables can be observed, it is not linear.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In this case the Pearson correlation coefficient does not indicate that there is an exact functional relationship: only the extent to which that relationship can be approximated by a linear relationship.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In the third case (bottom left), the linear relationship is perfect, except for one outlier which exerts enough influence to lower the correlation coefficient from 1 to 0.816.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Finally, the fourth example (bottom right) shows another example when one outlier is enough to produce a high correlation coefficient, even though the relationship between the two variables is not linear.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] These examples indicate that the correlation coefficient, as a summary statistic, cannot replace visual examination of the data.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The examples are sometimes said to demonstrate that the Pearson correlation assumes that the data follow a normal distribution, but this is only partially correct.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The Pearson correlation can be accurately calculated for any distribution that has a finite covariance matrix, which includes most distributions encountered in practice.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] However, the Pearson correlation coefficient (taken together with the sample mean and variance) is only a sufficient statistic if the data is drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] As a result, the Pearson correlation coefficient fully characterizes the relationship between variables if and only if the data are drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Similarly for two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ : If they are independent, then they are uncorrelated.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The opposite of this statement might not be true.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might not be independent of each other.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The degree of dependence between variables X and Y does not depend on the scale on which the variables are expressed.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] That is, if we are analyzing the relationship between X and Y, most correlation measures are unaffected by transforming X to *a* + *bX* and Y to *c* + *dY*, where *a*, *b*, *c*, and *d* are constants (*b* and *d* being positive).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This is true of some correlation statistics as well as their population analogues.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Some correlation statistics, such as the rank correlation coefficient, are also invariant to monotone transformations of the marginal distributions of X and/or Y.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Most correlation measures are sensitive to the manner in which X and Y are sampled.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Dependencies tend to be stronger if viewed over a wider range of values.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Several techniques have been developed that attempt to correct for range restriction in one or both variables, and are commonly used in meta-analysis; the most common are Thorndike's case II and case III equations.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Various correlation measures in use may be undefined for certain joint distributions of X and Y.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For example, the Pearson correlation coefficient is defined in terms of moments, and hence will be undefined if the moments are undefined.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Measures of dependence based on quantiles are always defined.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Sample-based statistics intended to estimate population measures of dependence may or may not have desirable statistical properties such as being unbiased, or asymptotically consistent, based on the spatial structure of the population from which the data were sampled.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Sensitivity to the data distribution can be used to an advantage.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For example, scaled correlation is designed to use the sensitivity to the range in order to pick out correlations between fast components of time series.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] By reducing the range of values in a controlled manner, the correlations on long time scale are filtered out and only the correlations on short time scales are revealed.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Thus the diagonal entries are all identically one.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] If the measures of correlation used are product-moment coefficients, the correlation matrix is the same as the covariance matrix of the standardized random variables $X_{i}/\sigma (X_{i})$ for $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This applies both to the matrix of population correlations (in which case $\sigma$ is the population standard deviation), and to the matrix of sample correlations (in which case $\sigma$ denotes the sample standard deviation).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Consequently, each is necessarily a positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Moreover, the correlation matrix is strictly positive definite if no variable can have all its values exactly generated as a linear function of the values of the others.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The correlation matrix is symmetric because the correlation between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ is the same as the correlation between $X_{j}$ and $X_{i}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] A correlation matrix appears, for example, in one formula for the coefficient of multiple determination, a measure of goodness of fit in multiple regression.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In statistical modelling, correlation matrices representing the relationships between variables are categorized into different correlation structures, which are distinguished by factors such as the number of parameters required to estimate them.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For example, in an exchangeable correlation matrix, all pairs of variables are modeled as having the same correlation, so all non-diagonal elements of the matrix are equal to each other.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] On the other hand, an autoregressive matrix is often used when variables represent a time series, since correlations are likely to be greater when measurements are closer in time.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Other examples include independent, unstructured, M-dependent, and Toeplitz.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In exploratory data analysis, the iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In some applications (e.g., building data models from only partially observed data) one wants to find the "nearest" correlation matrix to an "approximate" correlation matrix (e.g., a matrix which typically lacks positive semi-definiteness due to the way it has been computed).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] In 2002, Higham formalized the notion of nearness using the Frobenius norm and provided a method for computing the nearest correlation matrix using the Dykstra's projection algorithm.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This sparked interest in the subject, with new theoretical (e.g., computing the nearest correlation matrix with factor structure) and numerical (e.g. usage of Newton's method for computing the nearest correlation matrix) results obtained in the subsequent years.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] where $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (X)$ and $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (Y)$ are the expected values of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively, and $\ \sigma _{X}\$ and $\ \sigma _{Y}\$ are the standard deviations of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] where $\ F_{Hyp}\$ is the Gaussian hypergeometric function.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This density is both a Bayesian posterior density and an exact optimal confidence distribution density.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The information given by a correlation coefficient is not enough to define the dependence structure between random variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The correlation coefficient completely defines the dependence structure only in very particular cases, for example when the distribution is a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] (See diagram above.) In the case of elliptical distributions it characterizes the (hyper-)ellipses of equal density; however, it does not completely characterize the dependence structure (for example, a multivariate t-distribution's degrees of freedom determine the level of tail dependence).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For continuous variables, multiple alternative measures of dependence were introduced to address the deficiency of Pearson's correlation that it can be zero for dependent random variables (see and references therein for an overview).
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] They all share the important property that a value of zero implies independence.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This led some authors to recommend their routine usage, particularly of distance correlation.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Another alternative measure is the Randomized Dependence Coefficient.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The RDC is a computationally efficient, copula-based measure of dependence between multivariate random variables and is invariant with respect to non-linear scalings of random variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] One important disadvantage of the alternative, more general measures is that, when used to test whether two variables are associated, they tend to have lower power compared to Pearson's correlation when the data follow a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] This is an implication of the No free lunch theorem.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] To detect all kinds of relationships, these measures have to sacrifice power on other relationships, particularly for the important special case of a linear relationship with Gaussian marginals, for which Pearson's correlation is optimal.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Another problem concerns interpretation.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] While Pearson's correlation can be interpreted for all values, the alternative measures can generally only be interpreted meaningfully at the extremes.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] For two binary variables, the odds ratio measures their dependence, and takes a range of non-negative numbers, possibly infinity: ⁠ $[0,+\infty ]$ ⁠.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] Related statistics such as Yule's *Y* and Yule's *Q* normalize this to the correlation-like range ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠.
[src:multivariate-statistics/correlation] The odds ratio is generalized by the logistic model to model cases where the dependent variables are discrete and there may be one or more independent variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] In probability theory and statistics, a **covariance matrix** (also known as **auto-covariance matrix**, **dispersion matrix**, **variance matrix**, or **variance–covariance matrix**) is a square matrix giving the covariance between each pair of elements of a given random vector.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Intuitively, the covariance matrix generalizes the notion of variance to multiple dimensions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Any covariance matrix is symmetric and positive semi-definite and its main diagonal contains variances (i.e., the covariance of each element with itself).
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix of a random vector $\mathbf {X}$ is typically denoted by $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }$ , $\Sigma$ or S .
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Throughout this article, boldfaced unsubscripted $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ are used to refer to random vectors, and Roman subscripted $X_{i}$ and $Y_{i}$ are used to refer to scalar random variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Both forms are quite standard, and there is no ambiguity between them.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The matrix $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }$ is also often called the **variance-covariance matrix**, since the diagonal terms are in fact variances.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Each element on the principal diagonal of a correlation matrix is the correlation of a random variable with itself, which always equals 1.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Each off-diagonal element is between −1 and +1 inclusive.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The inverse of this matrix, $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {X} \mathbf {X} }^{-1}$ , if it exists, is the inverse covariance matrix, also known as the *precision matrix* (or *concentration matrix*).
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] This duality motivates a number of other dualities between marginalizing and conditioning for Gaussian random variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }$ and $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {YY} }$ can be identified as the variance matrices of the marginal distributions for $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ respectively.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The matrix $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {YX} }\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }^{-1}$ is known as the matrix of regression coefficients, while in linear algebra $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {Y|X} }$ is the Schur complement of $\operatorname {K} _{\mathbf {XX} }$ in ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] In this form they correspond to the coefficients obtained by inverting the matrix of the normal equations of ordinary least squares (OLS).
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] A covariance matrix with all non-zero elements tells us that all the individual random variables are interrelated.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] This means that the variables are not only directly correlated, but also correlated via other variables indirectly.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Often such indirect, common-mode correlations are trivial and uninteresting.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] They can be suppressed by calculating the partial covariance matrix, that is the part of covariance matrix that shows only the interesting part of correlations.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The standard deviation matrix $\mathbf {S}$ is the extension of the standard deviation to multiple dimensions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] It is the symmetric square root of the covariance matrix $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Applied to one vector, the covariance matrix maps a linear combination **c** of the random variables **X** onto a vector of covariances with those variables: $\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\Sigma =\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Treated as a bilinear form, it yields the covariance between the two linear combinations: $\mathbf {d} ^{\mathsf {T}}{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}\mathbf {c} =\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {d} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The variance of a linear combination is then $\mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}\mathbf {c}$ , its covariance with itself.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Similarly, the (pseudo-)inverse covariance matrix provides an inner product $\langle c-\mu |\Sigma ^{+}|c-\mu \rangle$ , which induces the Mahalanobis distance, a measure of the "unlikelihood" of *c*.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Conversely, every symmetric positive semi-definite matrix is a covariance matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] To see this, suppose M is a $p\times p$ symmetric positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] From the finite-dimensional case of the spectral theorem, it follows that M has a nonnegative symmetric square root, which can be denoted by **M**1/2.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Let $\mathbf {X}$ be any $p\times 1$ column vector-valued random variable whose covariance matrix is the $p\times p$ identity matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] If $\mathbf {Z} =(Z_{1},\ldots ,Z_{n})^{\mathsf {T}}$ is a column vector of complex-valued random variables, then the conjugate transpose $\mathbf {Z} ^{\mathsf {H}}$ is formed by *both* transposing and conjugating.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] In contrast to the covariance matrix defined above, Hermitian transposition gets replaced by transposition in the definition.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Its diagonal elements may be complex valued; it is a complex symmetric matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] These empirical sample covariance matrices are the most straightforward and most often used estimators for the covariance matrices, but other estimators also exist, including regularised or shrinkage estimators, which may have better properties.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix is a useful tool in many different areas.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] This is called principal component analysis (PCA) and the Karhunen–Loève transform (KL-transform).
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The covariance matrix plays a key role in financial economics, especially in portfolio theory and its mutual fund separation theorem and in the capital asset pricing model.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The matrix of covariances among various assets' returns is used to determine, under certain assumptions, the relative amounts of different assets that investors should (in a normative analysis) or are predicted to (in a positive analysis) choose to hold in a context of diversification.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The evolution strategy, a particular family of Randomized Search Heuristics, fundamentally relies on a covariance matrix in its mechanism.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The characteristic mutation operator draws the update step from a multivariate normal distribution using an evolving covariance matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Intuitively, this result is supported by the rationale that the optimal covariance distribution can offer mutation steps whose equidensity probability contours match the level sets of the landscape, and so they maximize the progress rate.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] In **covariance mapping** the values of the $\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} )$ or $\operatorname {pcov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} \mid \mathbf {I} )$ matrix are plotted as a 2-dimensional map.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] When vectors $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ are discrete random functions, the map shows statistical relations between different regions of the random functions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Statistically independent regions of the functions show up on the map as zero-level flatland, while positive or negative correlations show up, respectively, as hills or valleys.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] 1 illustrates how a partial covariance map is constructed on an example of an experiment performed at the FLASH free-electron laser in Hamburg.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The random function $X(t)$ is the time-of-flight spectrum of ions from a Coulomb explosion of nitrogen molecules multiply ionised by a laser pulse.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Since only a few hundreds of molecules are ionised at each laser pulse, the single-shot spectra are highly fluctuating.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] However, collecting typically $m=10^{4}$ such spectra, $\mathbf {X} _{j}(t)$ , and averaging them over j produces a smooth spectrum $\langle \mathbf {X} (t)\rangle$ , which is shown in red at the bottom of Fig.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The average spectrum $\langle \mathbf {X} \rangle$ reveals several nitrogen ions in a form of peaks broadened by their kinetic energy, but to find the correlations between the ionisation stages and the ion momenta requires calculating a covariance map.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] 1 spectra $\mathbf {X} _{j}(t)$ and $\mathbf {Y} _{j}(t)$ are the same, except that the range of the time-of-flight t differs.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Panel **a** shows $\langle \mathbf {XY^{\mathsf {T}}} \rangle$ , panel **b** shows $\langle \mathbf {X} \rangle \langle \mathbf {Y} ^{\mathsf {T}}\rangle$ and panel **c** shows their difference, which is $\operatorname {cov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} )$ (note a change in the colour scale).
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Unfortunately, this map is overwhelmed by uninteresting, common-mode correlations induced by laser intensity fluctuating from shot to shot.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] To suppress such correlations the laser intensity $I_{j}$ is recorded at every shot, put into $\mathbf {I}$ and $\operatorname {pcov} (\mathbf {X} ,\mathbf {Y} \mid \mathbf {I} )$ is calculated as panels **d** and **e** show.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] The suppression of the uninteresting correlations is, however, imperfect because there are other sources of common-mode fluctuations than the laser intensity and in principle all these sources should be monitored in vector $\mathbf {I}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Yet in practice it is often sufficient to overcompensate the partial covariance correction as panel **f** shows, where interesting correlations of ion momenta are now clearly visible as straight lines centred on ionisation stages of atomic nitrogen.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy employs correlation analysis to obtain 2D spectra of the condensed phase.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] There are two versions of this analysis: synchronous and asynchronous.
[src:multivariate-statistics/covariance-matrix] Mathematically, the former is expressed in terms of the sample covariance matrix and the technique is equivalent to covariance mapping.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] The **Hotelling's *t*-squared statistic** (***t*2**) is a generalization of Student's *t*-statistic that is used in multivariate hypothesis testing.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] The distribution arises in multivariate statistics in undertaking tests of the differences between the (multivariate) means of different populations, where tests for univariate problems would make use of a *t*-test.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] The distribution is named for Harold Hotelling, who developed it as a generalization of Student's *t*-distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] It can be shown that if a random variable *X* has Hotelling's *T*-squared distribution, $X\sim T_{p,m}^{2}$ , then: ${\frac {m-p+1}{pm}}X\sim F_{p,m-p+1}$ where $F_{p,m-p+1}$ is the *F*-distribution with parameters *p* and *m* − *p* + 1.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] where we denote transpose by an apostrophe.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] It can be shown that ${\hat {\mathbf {\Sigma } }}$ is a positive (semi) definite matrix and $(n-1){\hat {\mathbf {\Sigma } }}$ follows a *p*-variate Wishart distribution with *n* − 1 degrees of freedom.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] The sample covariance matrix of the mean reads ${\hat {\mathbf {\Sigma } }}_{\overline {\mathbf {x} }}={\hat {\mathbf {\Sigma } }}/n$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] which is proportional to the Mahalanobis distance between the sample mean and ${\boldsymbol {\mu }}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] Because of this, one should expect the statistic to assume low values if ${\overline {\mathbf {x} }}\approx {\boldsymbol {\mu }}$ , and high values if they are different.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] where $F_{p,n-p}$ is the *F*-distribution with parameters *p* and *n* − *p*.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] Then, use the quantity on the left hand side to evaluate the *p*-value corresponding to the sample, which comes from the *F*-distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] A confidence region may also be determined using similar logic.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] Let ${\mathcal {N}}_{p}({\boldsymbol {\mu }},{\mathbf {\Sigma } })$ denote a *p*-variate normal distribution with location ${\boldsymbol {\mu }}$ and known covariance ${\mathbf {\Sigma } }$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] be *n* independent identically distributed (iid) random variables, which may be represented as $p\times 1$ column vectors of real numbers.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] to be the sample mean with covariance ${\mathbf {\Sigma } }_{\overline {\mathbf {x} }}={\mathbf {\Sigma } }/n$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] where $\chi _{p}^{2}$ is the chi-squared distribution with *p* degrees of freedom.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] Alternatively, one can argue using density functions and characteristic functions, as follows.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] as the respective sample covariance matrices.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] is the unbiased **pooled covariance matrix** estimate (an extension of pooled variance).
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] In the two-variable case, the formula simplifies nicely allowing appreciation of how the correlation, $\rho$ , between the variables affects $t^{2}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] If the differences are of opposite sign $t^{2}$ becomes larger as $\rho$ becomes more positive.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] A univariate special case can be found in Welch's t-test.
[src:multivariate-statistics/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] More robust and powerful tests than the Hotelling's two-sample test have been proposed in the literature, see for example the interpoint distance based tests which can be applied also when the number of variables is comparable with, or even larger than, the number of subjects.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The **Mahalanobis distance** is a measure of the distance between a point P and a probability distribution D , introduced by P.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The mathematical details of Mahalanobis distance first appeared in the *Journal of The Asiatic Society of Bengal* in 1936.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Mahalanobis's definition was prompted by the problem of identifying the similarities of skulls based on measurements (the earliest work related to similarities of skulls are from 1922 and another later work is from 1927).
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Bose later obtained the sampling distribution of Mahalanobis distance, under the assumption of equal dispersion.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] It is a multivariate generalization of the square of the standard score $z=(x-\mu )/\sigma$ : how many standard deviations away P is from the mean of D .
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] This distance is zero for P at the mean of D and grows as P moves away from the mean along each principal component axis.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] If each of these axes is re-scaled to have unit variance, and whitened to be uncorrelated, then the Mahalanobis distance corresponds to standard Euclidean distance in the transformed space.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The Mahalanobis distance is thus unitless, scale-invariant, and takes into account the correlations of the data set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Since $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ is positive semi-definite, so is $\mathbf {\Sigma } ^{-1}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Thus, the square roots are always defined.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] We can find useful decompositions of the squared Mahalanobis distance that help to explain some reasons for the outlyingness of multivariate observations and also provide a graphical tool for identifying outliers.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] By the spectral theorem, $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ can be decomposed as $\mathbf {\Sigma } =\mathbf {S} ^{T}\mathbf {S}$ for some real $N\times N$ matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] One choice for $\mathbf {S}$ is the symmetric square root of $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ , which is the standard deviation matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] That is, the Mahalanobis distance is the Euclidean distance after a whitening transformation.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The existence of $\mathbf {S}$ is guaranteed by the spectral theorem, but it is not unique.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Different choices have different theoretical and practical advantages.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] In practice, the distribution Q is usually the sample distribution from a set of IID samples from an underlying unknown distribution, so $\mu$ is the sample mean, and $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ is the covariance matrix of the samples.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] When the affine span of the samples is not the entire $\mathbb {R} ^{N}$ , the covariance matrix would not be positive-definite, which means the above definition would not work.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] However, in general, the Mahalanobis distance is preserved under any full-rank affine transformation of the affine span of the samples.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] So in case the affine span is not the entire $\mathbb {R} ^{N}$ , the samples can be first orthogonally projected to $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , where n is the dimension of the affine span of the samples, then the Mahalanobis distance can be computed as usual.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Consider the problem of estimating the probability that a test point in *N*-dimensional Euclidean space belongs to a set, where we are given sample points that definitely belong to that set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Our first step would be to find the centroid or center of mass of the sample points.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Intuitively, the closer the point in question is to this center of mass, the more likely it is to belong to the set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] However, we also need to know if the set is spread out over a large range or a small range, so that we can decide whether a given distance from the center is noteworthy or not.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The simplistic approach is to estimate the standard deviation of the distances of the sample points from the center of mass.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] If the distance between the test point and the center of mass is less than one standard deviation, then we might conclude that it is highly probable that the test point belongs to the set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The further away it is, the more likely that the test point should not be classified as belonging to the set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] This intuitive approach can be made quantitative by defining the normalized distance between the test point and the set to be ${\frac {\lVert x-\mu \rVert _{2}}{\sigma }}$ , which reads: ${\frac {{\text{testpoint}}-{\text{sample mean}}}{\text{standard deviation}}}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] By plugging this into the normal distribution, we can derive the probability of the test point belonging to the set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The drawback of the above approach was that we assumed that the sample points are distributed about the center of mass in a spherical manner.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Were the distribution to be decidedly non-spherical, for instance ellipsoidal, then we would expect the probability of the test point belonging to the set to depend not only on the distance from the center of mass, but also on the direction.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] In those directions where the ellipsoid has a short axis the test point must be closer, while in those where the axis is long the test point can be further away from the center.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Putting this on a mathematical basis, the ellipsoid that best represents the set's probability distribution can be estimated by building the covariance matrix of the samples.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The Mahalanobis distance is the distance of the test point from the center of mass divided by the width of the ellipsoid in the direction of the test point.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Specifically, $d^{2}$ follows the chi-squared distribution with n degrees of freedom, where n is the number of dimensions of the normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] If the number of dimensions is 2, for example, the probability of a particular calculated d being less than some threshold t is $1-e^{-t^{2}/2}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] To determine a threshold to achieve a particular probability, p , use ${\textstyle t={\sqrt {-2\ln(1-p)}}}$ , for 2 dimensions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] For number of dimensions other than 2, the cumulative chi-squared distribution should be consulted.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] In a normal distribution, the region where the Mahalanobis distance is less than one (i.e. the region inside the ellipsoid at distance one) is exactly the region where the probability distribution is concave.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The Mahalanobis distance is proportional, for a normal distribution, to the square root of the negative log-likelihood (after adding a constant so the minimum is at zero).
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The sample mean and covariance matrix can be quite sensitive to outliers, therefore other approaches for calculating the multivariate location and scatter of data are also commonly used when calculating the Mahalanobis distance.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The Minimum Covariance Determinant approach estimates multivariate location and scatter from a subset numbering h data points that has the smallest variance-covariance matrix determinant.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The Minimum Volume Ellipsoid approach is similar to the Minimum Covariance Determinant approach in that it works with a subset of size h data points, but the Minimum Volume Ellipsoid estimates multivariate location and scatter from the ellipsoid of minimal volume that encapsulates the h data points.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Each method varies in its definition of the distribution of the data, and therefore produces different Mahalanobis distances.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The Minimum Covariance Determinant and Minimum Volume Ellipsoid approaches are more robust to samples that contain outliers, while the sample mean and covariance matrix tends to be more reliable with small and biased data sets.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] The resulting magnitude is always non-negative and varies with the distance of the data from the mean, attributes that are convenient when trying to define a model for the data.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Mahalanobis distance is widely used in cluster analysis and classification techniques.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] It is closely related to Hotelling's T-square distribution used for multivariate statistical testing and Fisher's linear discriminant analysis that is used for supervised classification.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] In order to use the Mahalanobis distance to classify a test point as belonging to one of *N* classes, one first estimates the covariance matrix of each class, usually based on samples known to belong to each class.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Then, given a test sample, one computes the Mahalanobis distance to each class, and classifies the test point as belonging to that class for which the Mahalanobis distance is minimal.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Mahalanobis distance and leverage are often used to detect outliers, especially in the development of linear regression models.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] A point that has a greater Mahalanobis distance from the rest of the sample population of points is said to have higher leverage since it has a greater influence on the slope or coefficients of the regression equation.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Mahalanobis distance is also used to determine multivariate outliers.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Regression techniques can be used to determine if a specific case within a sample population is an outlier via the combination of two or more variable scores.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Mahalanobis distance has also been used in ecological niche modelling, as the convex elliptical shape of the distances relates well to the concept of the fundamental niche.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Another example of usage is in finance, where Mahalanobis distance has been used to compute an indicator called the "turbulence index", which is a statistical measure of financial markets abnormal behaviour.
[src:multivariate-statistics/mahalanobis-distance] Many programming languages and statistical packages, such as R, Python, etc., include implementations of Mahalanobis distance.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] In probability theory and statistics, the **multivariate normal distribution**, **multivariate Gaussian distribution**, or **joint normal distribution** is a generalization of the one-dimensional (univariate) normal distribution to higher dimensions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] One definition is that a random vector is said to be *k*-variate normally distributed if every linear combination of its *k* components has a univariate normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Its importance derives mainly from the multivariate central limit theorem.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The multivariate normal distribution is often used to describe, at least approximately, any set of (possibly) correlated real-valued random variables, each of which clusters around a mean value.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] such that $1\leq i\leq k$ and $1\leq j\leq k$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The inverse of the covariance matrix is called the precision matrix, denoted by ${\boldsymbol {Q}}={\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}^{-1}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Here the covariance matrix is ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}={\boldsymbol {A}}{\boldsymbol {A}}^{\mathrm {T} }$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] In the degenerate case where the covariance matrix is singular, the corresponding distribution has no density; see the section below for details.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] This case arises frequently in statistics; for example, in the distribution of the vector of residuals in the ordinary least squares regression.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The $X_{i}$ are in general *not* independent; they can be seen as the result of applying the matrix ${\boldsymbol {A}}$ to a collection of independent Gaussian variables $\mathbf {Z}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The following definitions are equivalent to the definition given above.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] A random vector $\mathbf {X} =(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{k})^{\mathrm {T} }$ has a multivariate normal distribution if it satisfies one of the following equivalent conditions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The spherical normal distribution can be characterised as the unique distribution where components are independent in any orthogonal coordinate system.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The multivariate normal distribution is said to be "non-degenerate" when the symmetric covariance matrix ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ is positive definite.
