[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Each iso-density locus — the locus of points in *k*-dimensional space each of which gives the same particular value of the density — is an ellipse or its higher-dimensional generalization; hence the multivariate normal is a special case of the elliptical distributions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The quantity ${\sqrt {({\mathbf {x} }-{\boldsymbol {\mu }})^{\mathrm {T} }{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}^{-1}({\mathbf {x} }-{\boldsymbol {\mu }})}}$ is known as the Mahalanobis distance, which represents the distance of the test point ${\mathbf {x} }$ from the mean ${\boldsymbol {\mu }}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The squared Mahalanobis distance $({\mathbf {x} }-{\boldsymbol {\mu }})^{\mathrm {T} }{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}^{-1}({\mathbf {x} }-{\boldsymbol {\mu }})$ is decomposed into a sum of *k* terms, each term being a product of three meaningful components.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Note that in the case when $k=1$ , the distribution reduces to a univariate normal distribution and the Mahalanobis distance reduces to the absolute value of the standard score.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The bivariate iso-density loci plotted in the $x,y$ -plane are ellipses, whose principal axes are defined by the eigenvectors of the covariance matrix ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ (the major and minor semidiameters of the ellipse equal the square-root of the ordered eigenvalues).
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] This is because this expression, with $\operatorname {sgn}(\rho )$ (where sgn is the sign function) replaced by $\rho$ , is the best linear unbiased prediction of Y given a value of X .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] If the covariance matrix ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ is not full rank, then the multivariate normal distribution is degenerate and does not have a density.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] More precisely, it does not have a density with respect to *k*-dimensional Lebesgue measure (which is the usual measure assumed in calculus-level probability courses).
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Only random vectors whose distributions are absolutely continuous with respect to a measure are said to have densities (with respect to that measure).
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] To talk about densities meaningfully in singular cases, then, we must select a different base measure.
