[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] An affine transformation of **X** such as 2**X** is not the same as the sum of two independent realisations of **X**.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The equidensity contours of a non-singular multivariate normal distribution are ellipsoids (i.e. affine transformations of hyperspheres) centered at the mean.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Hence the multivariate normal distribution is an example of the class of elliptical distributions.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The directions of the principal axes of the ellipsoids are given by the eigenvectors of the covariance matrix ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The squared relative lengths of the principal axes are given by the corresponding eigenvalues.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Moreover, **U** can be chosen to be a rotation matrix, as inverting an axis does not have any effect on *N*(0, **Λ**), but inverting a column changes the sign of **U'**s determinant.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Conversely, any choice of **μ**, full rank matrix **U**, and positive diagonal entries Λ*i* yields a non-singular multivariate normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] If any Λ*i* is zero and **U** is square, the resulting covariance matrix **UΛU**T is singular.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Geometrically this means that every contour ellipsoid is infinitely thin and has zero volume in *n*-dimensional space, as at least one of the principal axes has length of zero; this is the degenerate case.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] In one dimension the probability of finding a sample of the normal distribution in the interval $\mu \pm \sigma$ is approximately 68.27%, but in higher dimensions the probability of finding a sample in the region of the standard deviation ellipse is lower.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The derivation of the maximum-likelihood estimator of the covariance matrix of a multivariate normal distribution is straightforward.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] which is simply the sample covariance matrix.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The Fisher information matrix for estimating the parameters of a multivariate normal distribution has a closed form expression.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] This can be used, for example, to compute the Cramér–Rao bound for parameter estimation in this setting.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] See Fisher information for more details.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] In Bayesian statistics, the conjugate prior of the mean vector is another multivariate normal distribution, and the conjugate prior of the covariance matrix is an inverse-Wishart distribution ${\mathcal {W}}^{-1}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Multivariate normality tests check a given set of data for similarity to the multivariate normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The null hypothesis is that the data set is similar to the normal distribution, therefore a sufficiently small *p*-value indicates non-normal data.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Multivariate normality tests include the Cox–Small test and Smith and Jain's adaptation of the Friedman–Rafsky test created by Larry Rafsky and Jerome Friedman.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Under the null hypothesis of multivariate normality, the statistic *A* will have approximately a chi-squared distribution with ⁠1/6⁠⋅*k*(*k* + 1)(*k* + 2) degrees of freedom, and *B* will be approximately standard normal *N*(0,1).
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Mardia's kurtosis statistic is skewed and converges very slowly to the limiting normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] For medium size samples $(50\leq n<400)$ , the parameters of the asymptotic distribution of the kurtosis statistic are modified For small sample tests ( $n<50$ ) empirical critical values are used.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Tables of critical values for both statistics are given by Rencher for *k* = 2, 3, 4.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Mardia's tests are affine invariant but not consistent.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] For example, the multivariate skewness test is not consistent against symmetric non-normal alternatives.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The **BHEP test** computes the norm of the difference between the empirical characteristic function and the theoretical characteristic function of the normal distribution.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Calculation of the norm is performed in the L2(*μ*) space of square-integrable functions with respect to the Gaussian weighting function $\mu _{\beta }(\mathbf {t} )=(2\pi \beta ^{2})^{-k/2}e^{-|\mathbf {t} |^{2}/(2\beta ^{2})}$ .
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] The limiting distribution of this test statistic is a weighted sum of chi-squared random variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] A detailed survey of these and other test procedures is available.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] Let **z** = (*z*1, ..., *zN*)T be a vector whose components are *N* independent standard normal variates (which can be generated, for example, by using the Box–Muller transform).
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-normal-distribution] This has the desired distribution due to the affine transformation property.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Multivariate analysis can be complicated by the desire to include physics-based analysis to calculate the effects of variables for a hierarchical "system-of-systems".
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Often, studies that wish to use multivariate analysis are stalled by the dimensionality of the problem.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] These concerns are often eased through the use of surrogate models, highly accurate approximations of the physics-based code.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Since surrogate models take the form of an equation, they can be evaluated very quickly.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] This becomes an enabler for large-scale MVA studies: while a Monte Carlo simulation across the design space is difficult with physics-based codes, it becomes trivial when evaluating surrogate models, which often take the form of response-surface equations.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Multivariate regression attempts to determine a formula that can describe how elements in a vector of variables respond simultaneously to changes in others.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] For linear relations, regression analyses here are based on forms of the general linear model.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Some suggest that multivariate regression is distinct from multivariable regression, however, that is debated and not consistently true across scientific fields.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Principal components analysis (PCA) creates a new set of orthogonal variables that contain the same information as the original set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] It rotates the axes of variation to give a new set of orthogonal axes, ordered so that they summarize decreasing proportions of the variation.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Factor analysis is similar to PCA but allows the user to extract a specified number of synthetic variables, fewer than the original set, leaving the remaining unexplained variation as error.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] The extracted variables are known as latent variables or factors; each one may be supposed to account for covariation in a group of observed variables.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Canonical correlation analysis finds linear relationships among two sets of variables; it is the generalised (i.e. canonical) version of bivariate correlation.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Redundancy analysis (RDA) is similar to canonical correlation analysis but allows the user to derive a specified number of synthetic variables from one set of (independent) variables that explain as much variance as possible in another (independent) set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] It is a multivariate analogue of regression.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Correspondence analysis (CA), or reciprocal averaging, finds (like PCA) a set of synthetic variables that summarise the original set.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] The underlying model assumes chi-squared dissimilarities among records (cases).
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Canonical (or "constrained") correspondence analysis (CCA) for summarising the joint variation in two sets of variables (like redundancy analysis); combination of correspondence analysis and multivariate regression analysis.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Multidimensional scaling comprises various algorithms to determine a set of synthetic variables that best represent the pairwise distances between records.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] The original method is principal coordinates analysis (PCoA; based on PCA).
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Discriminant analysis, or canonical variate analysis, attempts to establish whether a set of variables can be used to distinguish between two or more groups of cases.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) computes a linear predictor from two sets of normally distributed data to allow for classification of new observations.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Clustering systems assign objects into groups (called clusters) so that objects (cases) from the same cluster are more similar to each other than objects from different clusters.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Recursive partitioning creates a decision tree that attempts to correctly classify members of the population based on a dichotomous dependent variable.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Artificial neural networks extend regression and clustering methods to non-linear multivariate models.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Statistical graphics such as tours, parallel coordinate plots, scatterplot matrices can be used to explore multivariate data.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Simultaneous equations models involve more than one regression equation, with different dependent variables, estimated together.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Vector autoregression involves simultaneous regressions of various time series variables on their own and each other's lagged values.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Principal response curves analysis (PRC) is a method based on RDA that allows the user to focus on treatment effects over time by correcting for changes in control treatments over time.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] It is very common that in an experimentally acquired set of data the values of some components of a given data point are missing.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Rather than discarding the whole data point, it is common to "fill in" values for the missing components, a process called "imputation".
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] There is a set of probability distributions used in multivariate analyses that play a similar role to the corresponding set of distributions that are used in univariate analysis when the normal distribution is appropriate to a dataset.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] The Inverse-Wishart distribution is important in Bayesian inference, for example in Bayesian multivariate linear regression.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Additionally, Hotelling's T-squared distribution is a multivariate distribution, generalising Student's t-distribution, that is used in multivariate hypothesis testing.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Rao made significant contributions to multivariate statistical theory throughout his career, particularly in the mid-20th century.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] One of his key works is the book titled "Advanced Statistical Methods in Biometric Research," published in 1952.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] This work laid the foundation for many concepts in multivariate statistics.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] Anderson's 1958 textbook,*An Introduction to Multivariate Statistical Analysis*, educated a generation of theorists and applied statisticians; Anderson's book emphasizes hypothesis testing via likelihood ratio tests and the properties of power functions: admissibility, unbiasedness and monotonicity.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] MVA was formerly discussed solely in the context of statistical theories, due to the size and complexity of underlying datasets and its high computational consumption.
[src:multivariate-statistics/multivariate-statistics] With the dramatic growth of computational power, MVA now plays an increasingly important role in data analysis and has wide application in Omics fields.
